04740nam a22006735i 9781503603028DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2016049765  a97815036030287 a10.1515/97815036030282doi  a(DE-B1597)563907  a(OCoLC)1178770018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aKF274b.T45 2017 4aKF274 7aLAW0590002bisacsh04a340.071/1731 aTejani, Riaz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLaw Mart :bJustice, Access, and For-Profit Law Schools /cRiaz Tejani. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnthropology of Policy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Marketing Justice -- tChapter 1. Enrollment -- tChapter 2. "Charter Review" -- tChapter 3. The Legal Education Moral Economy Bubble -- tChapter 4. Law School 2.0 -- tChapter 5. Shared Governance in the Proprietary Legal Academy -- tChapter 6. "They Want the Rebels Gone" -- tChapter 7. The Policy Cascade -- tConclusion -- tAppendix. List of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican law schools are in deep crisis. Enrollment is down, student loan debt is up, and the profession's supply of high-paying jobs is shrinking. Meanwhile, thousands of graduates remain underemployed while the legal needs of low-income communities go substantially unmet. Many blame overregulation and seek a "free" market to solve the problem, but this has already been tested. Seizing on a deregulatory policy shift at the American Bar Association, private equity financiers established the first for-profit law schools in the early 2000s with the stated mission to increase access to justice by "serving the underserved". Pursuing this mission at a feverish rate of growth, they offered the promise of professional upward mobility through high-tech, simplified teaching and learning. In Law Mart, a vivid ethnography of one such environment, Riaz Tejani argues that the rise of for-profit law schools shows the limits of a market-based solution to American access to justice. Building on theories in law, political economy, and moral anthropology, Tejani reveals how for-profit law schools marketed themselves directly to ethnoracial and socioeconomic "minority" communities, relaxed admission standards, increased diversity, shook up established curricula, and saw student success rates plummet. They contributed to a dramatic rise in U.S. law student debt burdens while charging premium tuition financed up-front through federal loans over time. If economic theories have so influenced legal scholarship, what happens when they come to shape law school transactions, governance, and oversight? For students promised professional citizenship by these institutions, is there a need for protections that better uphold institutional quality and sustainability? Offering an unprecedented glimpse of this landscape, Law Mart is a colorful foray into these essential questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFor-profit universities and collegeszUnited States. 0aLaw schoolszUnited States. 0aLawxStudy and teachingxEconomic aspects. 4aLegal education. 4aanthropology. 4aethnography. 4alaw. 4amarkets. 4amorals. 4aneoliberalism. 4aorganizational culture. 4apolicy. 4aregulation. 7aLAW / Legal Education.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360302840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603028.jp